rved as 2nd Lieutenant US Army 1826-1829."}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Nine hours too late for Jeb Stuart","detail":"Woodbridge had served as 2nd Lieutenant in the US Army (1826-1829) before entering the Episcopal priesthood. By 1864 he had been Rector of the Monumental Church in Richmond for 21 years — one of the most prominent Episcopal congregations in the Confederacy. His willingness to make the dangerous overnight journey for Mrs. Stuart speaks to both his personal courage and his central place in Richmond's wartime religious community. (Historical accounts; FindAGrave; Wikipedia on Flora Stuart)","body":"On May 12, 1864, the day after General Jeb Stuart was mortally wounded at Yellow Tavern, Rev. Woodbridge escorted Flora Cooke Stuart on an overnight journey from Beaverdam, Virginia, to Richmond to reach her husband. The journey — by train to Ashland, then fifteen miles by ambulance wagon through rain and military detours — took well over nine hours. Stuart died before Flora could reach him.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"Thirty-five years in Richmond’s pulpit","body":"The West Point lieutenant turned priest held Monumental Church from 1843 until his death in 1878 — through secession, the war, and the fall of the city around him. On the Flora Stuart night a nervous Confederate sentinel nearly shot him."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"George Washington Woodbridge","first_name":"George","last_name":"Woodbridge","middle_name":"Washington","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST035"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"branch":"US Army","rank":"2nd Lieutenant","start_year":1826,"end_year":1829}],"career":[{"role":"2nd Lieutenant","organization":"US Army","start_year":1826,"